  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">APT (Animal Part Tracker), developed primarily at Janelia Research Campus, is a neural-network-based pose-estimation tool for tracking body parts of animals in video. Since its 2022 release on Zenodo, it has accumulated 11 citations across some of the most selective venues in biology, establishing a clear role in enabling reproducible behavioral neuroscience research.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">APT was created by a team led by Kristin Branson and colleagues at Janelia Research Campus, with contributions from John Brown University and other collaborators. The software combines a graphical user interface with scriptable, extensible neural network backends\u2014implemented in MATLAB\u2014to allow researchers to label animal body parts in video frames and train customized tracking models without requiring deep machine-learning expertise. By lowering the technical barrier to high-throughput pose estimation, APT targets a practical gap that is acutely felt in experimental neuroscience, where precise quantification of animal movement is central to understanding circuit function and behavior.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The tool's citation trajectory signals rapid and sustained uptake. After its 2022 deposition, citations grew steadily through 2023 and accelerated in 2024 and 2025, with citing works appearing in Cell, Nature, eLife, Current Biology, and bioRxiv\u2014an unusually high-visibility spread for a software release archived on Zenodo. Roughly half of the citing works are preprints, indicating that researchers are integrating APT into active, ongoing projects rather than citing it retrospectively. The median citation count of works that themselves cite APT underscores that it is being adopted within productive, well-connected research programs.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The thematic profile of the citing literature is highly coherent: neuroscience and Drosophila biology dominate, with recurring clusters around mushroom body circuitry, associative learning, connectomics, and descending motor control. Representative citing works include a Cell paper on fine-grained steering control in walking Drosophila, a Nature study on whole-body physics simulation of fruit fly locomotion, and an eLife series on genetic driver lines for studying associative learning\u2014all contexts where frame-by-frame limb and body tracking is indispensable. This pattern suggests APT has become a go-to infrastructure tool within the Drosophila behavioral neuroscience community, functioning as a computational reproducibility enabler by providing a shared, citable method for pose quantification.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Institutionally, the citing community is anchored in research-intensive facilities, with Janelia Research Campus and Howard Hughes Medical Institute together accounting for the largest share of fractional authorship, followed by Harvard University, the University of Rochester Medical Center, and institutions in Israel, Germany, and the United Kingdom. This geographic spread, while still US-centric, indicates the tool is beginning to diffuse internationally. The software is openly accessible via Zenodo with a persistent DOI and is linked to an actively maintained GitHub repository, providing the version control and accessibility that support reproducible workflows. Taken together, the evidence positions APT as a maturing community resource whose scientific footprint, concentrated in high-impact systems neuroscience, is still growing.</p>",
